{"title_page": "Kushagra Rawat", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian swimmer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Kushagra Rawat\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| nationality    = Indian\n| strokes        = Freestyle\n| club           = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|2000|2|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| show-medals    = \n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n'''Kushagra Rawat''' (born 16 February 2000) is an Indian [[Swimming (sport)|swimmer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/field/919275/swimming-kushagra-rawat-one-step-closer-to-qualifying-for-olympics-and-world-championships |title=Swimming: Kushagra Rawat one step closer to qualifying for Olympics and World Championships |work=Scroll India |accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref> He competed in the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metre freestyle|men's 400 metre freestyle]] at the [[2019 World Aquatics Championships]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/00011301070101EF01FFFFFFFFFFFF00.pdf |title=18th FINA World Championships 2019: Men's 400m Freestyle start list |work=FINA |accessdate=21 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720085930/http://www.omegatiming.com/File/00011301070101EF01FFFFFFFFFFFF00.pdf |archive-date=20 July 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rawat, Kushagra}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male swimmers]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{India-swimming-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian swimmer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Kushagra Rawat\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| nationality    = Indian\n| strokes        = Freestyle\n| club           = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|2000|2|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| show-medals    = \n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n'''Kushagra Rawat''' (born 16 February 2000) is an Indian [[Swimming (sport)|swimmer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/field/919275/swimming-kushagra-rawat-one-step-closer-to-qualifying-for-olympics-and-world-championships |title=Swimming: Kushagra Rawat one step closer to qualifying for Olympics and World Championships |work=Scroll India |accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref> He competed in the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metre freestyle|men's 400 metre freestyle]] at the [[2019 World Aquatics Championships]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://omegatiming.com/File/00011301070101EF01FFFFFFFFFFFF00.pdf |title=18th FINA World Championships 2019: Men's 400m Freestyle start list |work=FINA |accessdate=21 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720085930/http://www.omegatiming.com/File/00011301070101EF01FFFFFFFFFFFF00.pdf |archive-date=20 July 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rawat, Kushagra}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male swimmers]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{India-swimming-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kushagra_Rawat"}
{"title_page": "Potato production in Nigeria", "text_new": "[[Nigeria]] is one of the largest producer of potatoes in Africa. The potato was introduced to the country in the 19th-century by Christian missionaries and is largely cultivated in the central region of the country in [[Plateau State]].\n\n==History==\nThe [[Irish potato]] was first brought into Nigeria in the 19th-century by Christian missionaries. During [[World War II]], the colonial government encouraged Nigerian farmers to grow potatoes to feed British troops stationed in [[West Africa]].{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=291}} A handful of European potato varieties, including pinepernel, ackersegen, dekema, and roslin eburu were introduced to Nigeria afterwards to little success. In the early 1970s, the State Ministry of Agriculture in [[Benue State|Benue]] took in another set of varieties including ajax, mirka, spunta, Nicola, desiree, diamant, dan-Cameroon, alpha, cardinal and Baraka.{{Sfn|Aniedu|2015|p=1}} In 1976, the Potato Research Programme of the National Roots Research Institute was established in [[Kuru, Nigeria|Kuru]], to look into ways of improving potato production in the country. In 1986, yet another set of varieties was imported into Nigeria: kondor, bertita, delcora, vento, famosa and romano.{{Sfn|Aniedu|2015|p=2}}\n\n==Production==\n{{nutritionalvalue\n| name=Potato, raw, with skin\n| water=75 g\n| kJ=321\n| protein=2 g\n| carbs=17.47 g\n| fat=0.1 g\n| fiber=2.2 g\n| starch=15.44 g\n| calcium_mg=12\n| iron_mg=0.78\n| magnesium_mg=23\n| phosphorus_mg=57\n| potassium_mg=421\n| sodium_mg=6\n| zinc_mg=0.29\n| manganese_mg=0.153\n| vitC_mg=19.7\n| thiamin_mg=0.08\n| riboflavin_mg=0.03\n| pantothenic_mg=0.296\n| vitB6_mg=0.295\n| folate_ug=16\n| vitE_mg=0.01\n| niacin_mg=1.05\n| vitK_ug=1.9\n| source_usda=1\n| right=1\n| note=[http://ndb.nal.usda.gov/ndb/search/list?qlookup=11352&format=Full Link to USDA Database entry]\n}}\n\nThe potato is a [[tuber]] crop which has high nutritional value. It has [[protein]], [[calcium]] and [[vitamin C]]. One potato of medium size contains 50 percent of the daily vitamin C needs of an adult. When boiled, its protein content is reported to be more than that of [[maize]], with double the calcium content.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.currentconcerns.ch/index.php?id=698|title=2008 \u2013 The International Year of the Potato|accessdate=20 April 2020|publisher=Current Concerns Journal}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2013 study, Nigeria ranks seventh among potato-producing countries in Africa and fourth in [[Sub-Saharan Africa]],{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=292}} with an annual production yield of around {{Convert|843,000|t}} and an actual planted area of {{Convert|270,000|ha}}.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=293}} In spite of that, the average yield in Nigeria of 3.1 tonnes/ha is among the world's lowest.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=293}}\n\nPotato production in Nigeria predominantly occurs in small farms whose farmers still rely on traditional tools as machetes and hoes as opposed to tractors.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=293}} According to a 2012 study, an estimated 300,000 households in Nigeria engage in potato production, which translates to an average planted area of {{Convert|1|ha}} per household each year.{{Sfn|Plaisier et al|2019|p=14}} The country's main potato-planting region is the [[Plateau State]] ([[Barkin Ladi]], [[Bokkos]], and [[Mangu, Nigeria|Mangu]]) which accounts for almost half of the national potato yield.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=293}}{{Sfn|Plaisier et al|2019|p=14}} Other potato-producing areas include [[Kaduna]] and Benue. Potato production takes place in both the wet season (April till August) and the dry season (September till March). Additionally, a low level of production occurs from October till January in [[Kano]].{{Sfn|Plaisier et al|2019|p=14}}\n\nThe potatoes are then graded by the Potato Research Programme. On average, some {{Convert|200,000|t}} of locally farmed potatoes are sold within the country each year while another 100,000 tonnes are unofficially sold across the West African borders.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=296}} Potato production in Nigeria faces many constraints, including the unavailability of good-quality potato seeds, poor storage methods, insufficient education on farming methods and pest control, inadequate research and development, and inadequate farming equipment.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=297}}\n\n==Cuisine==\nThe potato is regarded as the fourth most important root crop in Nigeria, following the [[cassava]], [[yam (vegetable)|yam]], and [[cocoyam]].{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=292}} [[French fries]] and [[potato crisps]] are widely consumed in Nigeria, with locally produced potatoes being used to make Monties and The Kings potato crisps.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=296}} However, the majority of potato-based snacks in the country are still imported.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=297}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal|journal=Journal of Agriculture and Social Research|volume=15|number=2|year=2015|last=Aniedu|first=Onymechi|title=Production system and varietal effects on potato production in Jos Plateau, Nigeria|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Ugonna|first=Charity|year=2013|title=A technical appraisal of potato value chain in Nigeria|journal=International Research Journal of Agricultural Science and Soil Science|volume=3|pages=291\u2013301|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|title=The vegetable and potato sector in Nigeria : an overview of the present status|last1=Plaisier|first1=Christine|last2=Dijkxhoorn|first2=Youri|last3=Rijn|first3=F\u00e9des van|last4=Bonnand|first4=Johann|last5=Talabi|first5=Olufolajimi|publisher=Wageningen Economic Research|journal=Wageningen Economic Research|isbn=9789463951876|url=https://edepot.wur.nl/504921|year=2019|ref={{SfnRef|Plaisier et al|2019}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{world topic|Potato production in|title = Potato production|noredlinks=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nigeria, potato production in}}\n[[Category:Agriculture in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Potato production]]\n", "text_old": "[[Nigeria]] is one of the largest producer of potatoes in Africa. The potato was introduced to the country in the 19th-century by Christian missionaries and is largely cultivated in the central region of the country in [[Plateau State]].\n\n==History==\nThe [[Irish potato]] was first brought into Nigeria in the 19th-century by Christian missionaries. During [[World War II]], the colonial government encouraged Nigerian farmers to grow potatoes to feed British troops stationed in [[West Africa]].{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=291}} A handful of European potato varieties, including pinepernel, ackersegen, dekema, and roslin eburu were introduced to Nigeria afterwards to little success. In the early 1970s, the State Ministry of Agriculture in [[Benue]] took in another set of varieties including ajax, mirka, spunta, Nicola, desiree, diamant, dan-Cameroon, alpha, cardinal and Baraka.{{Sfn|Aniedu|2015|p=1}} In 1976, the Potato Research Programme of the National Roots Research Institute was established in [[Kuru, Nigeria|Kuru]], to look into ways of improving potato production in the country. In 1986, yet another set of varieties was imported into Nigeria: kondor, bertita, delcora, vento, famosa and romano.{{Sfn|Aniedu|2015|p=2}}\n\n==Production==\n{{nutritionalvalue\n| name=Potato, raw, with skin\n| water=75 g\n| kJ=321\n| protein=2 g\n| carbs=17.47 g\n| fat=0.1 g\n| fiber=2.2 g\n| starch=15.44 g\n| calcium_mg=12\n| iron_mg=0.78\n| magnesium_mg=23\n| phosphorus_mg=57\n| potassium_mg=421\n| sodium_mg=6\n| zinc_mg=0.29\n| manganese_mg=0.153\n| vitC_mg=19.7\n| thiamin_mg=0.08\n| riboflavin_mg=0.03\n| pantothenic_mg=0.296\n| vitB6_mg=0.295\n| folate_ug=16\n| vitE_mg=0.01\n| niacin_mg=1.05\n| vitK_ug=1.9\n| source_usda=1\n| right=1\n| note=[http://ndb.nal.usda.gov/ndb/search/list?qlookup=11352&format=Full Link to USDA Database entry]\n}}\n\nThe potato is a [[tuber]] crop which has high nutritional value. It has [[protein]], [[calcium]] and [[vitamin C]]. One potato of medium size contains 50 percent of the daily vitamin C needs of an adult. When boiled, its protein content is reported to be more than that of [[maize]], with double the calcium content.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.currentconcerns.ch/index.php?id=698|title=2008 \u2013 The International Year of the Potato|accessdate=20 April 2020|publisher=Current Concerns Journal}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2013 study, Nigeria ranks seventh among potato-producing countries in Africa and fourth in [[Sub-Saharan Africa]],{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=292}} with an annual production yield of around {{Convert|843,000|t}} and an actual planted area of {{Convert|270,000|ha}}.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=293}} In spite of that, the average yield in Nigeria of 3.1 tonnes/ha is among the world's lowest.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=293}}\n\nPotato production in Nigeria predominantly occurs in small farms whose farmers still rely on traditional tools as machetes and hoes as opposed to tractors.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=293}} According to a 2012 study, an estimated 300,000 households in Nigeria engage in potato production, which translates to an average planted area of {{Convert|1|ha}} per household each year.{{Sfn|Plaisier et al|2019|p=14}} The country's main potato-planting region is the [[Plateau State]] ([[Barkin Ladi]], [[Bokkos]], and [[Mangu]]) which accounts for almost half of the national potato yield.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=293}}{{Sfn|Plaisier et al|2019|p=14}} Other potato-producing areas include [[Kaduna]] and Benue. Potato production takes place in both the wet season (April till August) and the dry season (September till March). Additionally, a low level of production occurs from October till January in [[Kano]].{{Sfn|Plaisier et al|2019|p=14}}\n\nThe potatoes are then graded by the Potato Research Programme. On average, some {{Convert|200,000|t}} of locally farmed potatoes are sold within the country each year while another 100,000 tonnes are unofficially sold across the West African borders.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=296}} Potato production in Nigeria faces many constraints, including the unavailability of good-quality potato seeds, poor storage methods, insufficient education on farming methods and pest control, inadequate research and development, and inadequate farming equipment.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=297}}\n\n==Cuisine==\nThe potato is regarded as the fourth most important root crop in Nigeria, following the [[cassava]], [[yam]], and [[cocoyam]].{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=292}} [[French fries]] and [[potato crisps]] are widely consumed in Nigeria, with locally produced potatoes being used to make Monties and The Kings potato crisps.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=296}} However, the majority of potato-based snacks in the country are still imported.{{Sfn|Ugonna|2013|p=297}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal|journal=Journal of Agriculture and Social Research|volume=15|number=2|year=2015|last=Aniedu|first=Onymechi|title=Production system and varietal effects on potato production in Jos Plateau, Nigeria|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Ugonna|first=Charity|year=2013|title=A technical appraisal of potato value chain in Nigeria|journal=International Research Journal of Agricultural Science and Soil Science|volume=3|pages=291\u2013301|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|title=The vegetable and potato sector in Nigeria : an overview of the present status|last1=Plaisier|first1=Christine|last2=Dijkxhoorn|first2=Youri|last3=Rijn|first3=F\u00e9des van|last4=Bonnand|first4=Johann|last5=Talabi|first5=Olufolajimi|publisher=Wageningen Economic Research|journal=Wageningen Economic Research|isbn=9789463951876|url=https://edepot.wur.nl/504921|year=2019|ref={{SfnRef|Plaisier et al|2019}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{world topic|Potato production in|title = Potato production|noredlinks=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nigeria, potato production in}}\n[[Category:Agriculture in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Potato production]]\