 Yellow And Blue / The Victors-March |title-link= |others=Wilfred Wilson, Director |year=1926 |publisher=Victor Talking Machine Co. |id=19971 |location=Camden, NJ }}</ref>\n\n=== Other album appearances ===\n* Various Artists: ''Gameday Faves: Classic College Fight Songs (Volume 2)'': \"The Victors - Michigan Wolverines (Live)\" (2008)<ref name=\"Gameday Faves 2\">{{cite web |title=Gameday Faves: Classic College Fight Songs (Volume 2) |url=https://www.amazon.com/Gameday-Faves-Classic-College-Fight/dp/B002OUTGAO/ref=sr_1_1?dchild=1&keywords=Gameday+Faves%3A+Classic+College+Fight+Songs+%28Volume+2%29&qid=1587182092&sr=8-1 |website=Amazon |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Destiny's Child]]: ''[[Destiny Fulfilled]]'': \"[[Lose My Breath]],\" drum cadence sample (2004)<ref name=\"Destiny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.michigandaily.com/content/free-samples|title=Free Samples|work=[[The Michigan Daily]]|publisher=[[University of Michigan]]|date=2006-11-30|accessdate=2013-01-26}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Documentaries ===\n* ''The Band Director'' (1975)<ref>{{Citation | title = \"The Band Director\" Wins Two Awards | journal = Music at Michigan | volume = 9 | issue = 1 | pages = 1 | publisher = The University of Michigan School of Music | location = Ann Arbor | date = July 1975 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7nQJAQAAMAAJ&lpg=RA1-PA10&ots=eX7sXuVJtQ&dq=%22The%20Band%20Director%22%20%22university%20of%20Michigan%22%20documentary&pg=RA1-PA11#v=onepage&q=%22The%20Band%20Director%22&f=false}}</ref>\n* ''Marching For Roses'' (1971)<ref>{{Citation | title = Educational film/video locator of the Consortium of University Film Centers and R.R. Bowker | volume=2 | date = 1986 | pages = 1953 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=tn4OAQAAMAAJ&q=%22rose+bowl%22+1979+%22michigan+Marching+Band%22&dq=%22rose+bowl%22+1979+%22michigan+Marching+Band%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwio55rKivvhAhVB0KwKHTXTArcQ6AEIQzAF\n | access-date=2019-05-01 | quote=Documents the University of Michigan Marching Band in its various stages of preparation for the 1970 Rose Bowl performance in Pasadena...  }}</ref>\n* ''Pow Pow'' (1960)<ref>{{Citation | title = Two Film Shows Set In Center Series | newspaper = The National Jewish POST and OPINION | date = 15 November 1963 | pages = 2 | url = https://newspapers.library.in.gov/cgi-bin/imageserver.pl?oid=JPOST19631115-01&getpdf=true\n | access-date=2019-04-30 | quote=\u201cPow Pow\u201d produced in 1960 is a lark, through the rain, with telephoto lens, dissecting the University of Michigan marching band. The band\u2019s purposefulness, high seriousness, and utter dedication are shown as never before.  }}</ref>\n* ''Here Comes the Band'' (1951)<ref>{{cite book |date=1952 |title=Catalog of Copyright Entries: Third series |publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]] |page=18 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FS4hAQAAIAAJ&lpg=RA2-PA18&ots=lgNtSbgWfn&dq=RKO%20Pathe%20%22here%20comes%20the%20band%22&pg=RA2-PA18#v=onepage&q=%22Here%20Comes%20the%20Band%22&f=false |website=books.google.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-30 |quote=Summary: A behind-the-scene story which shows the practice and drilling required to train the University of Michigan's 150-men marching band for their performance at each football game.}}</ref>\n\n=== Soundtrack contributions ===\n* ''Love, Simon'': \"Bad Romance,\" \"What Is Love\" (2018)<ref name=\"IMDbSountracks\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1681451/|title=University of Michigan Marching Band - IMDb|website=imdb.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n* ''Deliver Us from Eva'': \"The Victors\" (2003)<ref name=\"IMDbSountracks\"/>\n* ''Bicentennial Man'': \"The Washington Post\" (1999)<ref name=\"IMDbSountracks\"/>\n* ''The Waterboy'': \"Entry Cadence,\" \"Temptation,\" \"Hawaiian War Chant\" (1998)<ref name=\"IMDbSountracks\"/>\n* ''The Sixth Man'': \"Let's Go Blue\" (1997)<ref name=\"IMDbSountracks\"/>\n\n=== Television appearances ===\n* ''[[Good Morning America]]'' (October 4, 2002)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071755099/407 |title='Good Morning America' tours 'U,' state on broadcast |date=2006-10-07 |website=michigandaily.com |publisher=The Michigan Daily |access-date=2019-05-06 }}</ref>\n* ''[[Live with Kelly and Ryan#1988\u20132000: Live with Regis and Kathie Lee|Live with Regis and Kathie Lee]]'' (November 20, 1992)<ref name=\"DFP-LRKL\" />\n* ''A [[Bob Hope]] Celebration'' (October 22, 1981)<ref name=\"Bob-Hope-Memories\" />\n* ''The Music Shop'' (1974)<ref>{{cite AV media | people=Jerry H. Bilik | title=THE MUSIC SHOP | medium=Television production | publisher=The University of Michigan Television Center | location=Ann Arbor, Michigan | date=1974 | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t4GNeoUVcbE }}</ref>\n* ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'' (October 28, 1955)<ref>{{Citation | title=The Michigan Alumnus | place=Ann Arbor | publisher=UM Libraries | volume=62 | year=1955 | page=81 | quote=Early risers  on October 28 got an extra taste of stadium glory: Dave Garroway's \"Today\" television program featured the Michigan Marching Band... }}</ref><ref name=\"Mdaily19560511\">{{cite news | title='U' Marching Band Ends Active Year | page=5 | newspaper=The Michigan Daily | location=Ann Arbor | date=11 May 1956 | url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071756386/489 | quote=...appeared five times on television within a period of one week. Making up the band's five TV appearances were two high stepping sessions on Dave Garroway's \"Today\" show, a short program on Arlene Francis's \"Home Show,\"... }}</ref>\n* ''[[Home (1954 TV program)|Home]]'' (October, 1955)<ref name=\"Mdaily19560511\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Michigan Marching Band}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.michiganmarchingband.com}}\n\n{{University of Michigan|studentlife}}\n{{Michigan Wolverines football navbox}}\n{{Michigan Wolverines men's soccer navbox}}\n{{Big Ten Conference marching band navbox}}\n{{Sudler Trophy}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:College marching bands in the United States]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Music of Ann Arbor, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1896]]\n[[Category:1896 establishments in Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "JNmich", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michigan_Marching_Band"}
{"title_page": "Gilbertsville, Kentucky", "text_new": "'''Gilbertsville''' is [[census-designated place]] and [[unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in [[Marshall County, Kentucky|Marshall County]], [[Kentucky]], [[United States]]. Its elevation is 351&nbsp;feet (107&nbsp;m), and it is located at {{coord|37|1|28|N|88|17|59|W|type:city}} (37.0245003, -88.2997557).<ref>{{gnis|492823}}</ref> It is known as the closest village to [[Kentucky Dam]]. The town was relocated to its present site when [[Kentucky Dam]] and [[Kentucky Dam Village State Resort Park]] replaced the former site.\n\n==History==\n\n===Old Gilbertsville===\nThe original town of Gilbertsville was founded in 1871 near the [[Tennessee River]] as \"Clear Pond,\" named for a nearby lake. In 1874 it was incorporated and renamed \"Gilbertsville\" in honor of [[Jesse C. Gilbert]], who served as a Kentucky state senator from 1871 to 1875.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3Lac2FUSj_oC&lpg=PA49&dq=cannon%20ky&pg=PA115#v=onepage&q=cannon%20ky&f=false | title=Kentucky Place Names | publisher=University Press of Kentucky | date=1987 | accessdate=2013-04-28 | author=Rennick, Robert M. | pages=115}}</ref> The town grew to include a bank, several stores, a jail, and a school teaching grades 1-12. It had a population of approximately 300 in 1930.<ref name=Huddleston>\"Marshall County,\" by Connie M. Huddleston, Carol Aldridge, and Virginia Smith, Arcadia Publishing, 2005, {{ISBN|978-0-7385-4284-3}}. Retrieved January 20, 2010.</ref> The village thrived because besides the fertile bottomland, it afforded the combination of river access for transportation and fishing, and railroad transportation via the [[Illinois Central]] railroad.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/handbookkentuck00statgoog/page/n610 <!-- quote=\"Gilbertsville\" kentucky. -->]\"Handbook of Kentucky,\" by Hubert Vreeland, Commissioner of Agriculture. Louisville, Kentucky: The Globe Printing Co., 1908. Page 537. Retrieved January 20, 2010.</ref>\n\n===Modern Gilbertsville===\nThe construction of Kentucky Dam (1938\u20131944) meant the end for old Gilbertsville. The town was moved to its present site, initially called \"West Gilbertsville,\" with the geographic coordinates given above, by the time Kentucky Lake was impounded in the early 1940s.<ref name=Huddleston/> A notable event in the town's history was the dedication ceremony for Kentucky Dam on October 10, 1945, at which President [[Harry Truman]] gave the dedicatory speech.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=d0uu-j32elUC&pg=PA119&dq=%22Gilbertsville%22+kentucky&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&as_brr=3&cd=39#v=onepage&q=%22Gilbertsville%22%20kentucky&f=false] \"Conflict and crisis: the presidency of Harry S. Truman, 1945-1948.\" by Robert J. Donovan, University of Missouri Press, 1996. {{ISBN|978-0-8262-1066-1}}. Page 119. Retrieved January 20, 2010.</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FL4wAAAAIBAJ&sjid=pU4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=7038,3723457&dq=kentucky+gilbertsville&hl=en]\"Program for progress,\" St. Petersburg Times, October 11, 1945, page 4. Retrieved January 20, 2010</ref> Gilbertsville was a 6th class city from 1956 to 1976.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3Lac2FUSj_oC&pg=PA115&dq=%22Gilbertsville%22+kentucky&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&as_brr=3&cd=8#v=onepage&q=%22Gilbertsville%22%20kentucky&f=false] \"Kentucky Place Names,\" by Robert M. Rennick. The University Press of Kentucky, 1988, {{ISBN|978-0-8131-0179-8}}, Page 115. retrieved January 20, 2010.</ref> The town incorporated at its new site circa 1953. The town later abandoned its incorporated status in 1976 by a referendum. Before dissolving its charter, the town of 241 had a budget of $2,000 to $3,000 per year, which paid for a town marshal, street lights, and street repairs.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ByMqAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0UYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6662,25910&dq=kentucky+gilbertsville&hl=en]\"Gilbertsville concerned about 2 questions,\" by Bill Bergstrom, Associated Press. In the Daily News (Bowling Green, Kentucky), June 1, 1976.</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NrU0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=y2gFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1208,6357522&dq=kentucky+gilbertsville&hl=en]\"A still small voice.\" (Editorial). [[Kentucky New Era]] (Hopkinsville, Kentucky),May 28, 1976, page 21. Retrieved January 20, 2010.</ref>  It has been the site, for several decades, of the {{convert|25|acre|m2|adj=on}} Kentucky Sheriff's Boys and Girls Ranch, which has provided a free week-long summer camp for children ages 8\u201311, with total attendance of 30,000 through 2008.<ref>[http://www.timesleader.net/articles/stories/public/200806/04/4Okk_news.html]\"Sheriffs' Ranch open for summer session; boys, girls 8-11 invited to participate.\" The Times Leader (Princeton, Kentucky), June 4, 2008. Retrieved January 20, 2010</ref> Tourism related to the dams and lakes created nearby by [[Tennessee Valley Authority|TVA]] has driven the economy of the town since the 1940s. The town has an airport, an 18-hole golf course, a large marina, and has been the site of bass fishing tournaments<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/outdoors/tournaments/elite/news/story?id=3442226]\"On the ledge of success'\" by Lynn Burkhead, ESPNOutdoors.com August 13, 2008. Retrieved January 20, 2010</ref> and a car racing track.\n\n==Climate==\nThe climate in this area is characterized by hot, humid summers and generally mild to cool winters. According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, Gilbertsville has a [[humid subtropical climate]], abbreviated \"Cfa\" on climate maps.<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=322351&cityname=Gilbertsville%2C+Kentucky%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for Gilbertsville, Kentucky]</ref>\n\n==Annual events==\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://parks.ky.gov/calendar/default.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-05-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504133000/http://parks.ky.gov/calendar/default.aspx |archive-date=2014-05-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Arts and Crafts Festival\u2014Every Memorial Day Weekend the festival is located at the Old Beach Area and features handcrafted items by artists from Kentucky and neighboring states.\n* Earth Day Celebration\u2014Located at the Kentucky Dam Village Resort the festival features activities to celebrate Earth Day.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Gilbertsville, Kentucky}}\n* [http://www.uky.edu/KentuckyAtlas/ky-gilbertsville.html] Kentucky Atlas and Gazetteer, showing present location of Gilbertsville.\n\n\n{{Marshall County, Kentucky}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Marshall County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Populated places disestablished in 1976]]\n", "text_old": "'''Gilbertsville''' is [[census-designated place]] and [[unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in [[Marshall County, Kentucky|Marshall County]], [[Kentucky]], [[United States]]. Its elevation is 351&nbsp;feet (107&nbsp;m), and it is located at {{coord|37|1|28|N|88|17|59|W|type:city}} (37.0245003, -88.2997557).<ref>{{gnis|492823}}</ref> It is known as the closest village to [[Kentucky Dam]]. The town was relocated to its present site when [[Kentucky Dam]] and [[Kentucky Dam Village State Resort Park]] replaced the former site.\n\n==History==\n\n===Old Gilbertsville===\nThe original town of Gilbertsville was founded in 1871 near the [[Tennessee River]] as \"Clear Pond,\" named for a nearby lake. In 1874 it was incorporated and renamed \"Gilbertsville\" in honor of [[Jesse C. Gilbert]], who served as a Kentucky state senator from 1871 to 1875.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3Lac2FUSj_oC&lpg=PA49&dq=cannon%20ky&pg=PA115#v=onepage&q=cannon%20ky&f=false | title=Kentucky Place Names | publisher=University Press of Kentucky | date=1987 | accessdate=2013-04-28 | author=Rennick, Robert M. | pages=115}}</ref> The town grew to include a bank, several stores, a jail, and a school teaching grades 1-12. It had a population of approximately 300 in 1930.<ref name=Huddleston>\"Marshall County,\" by Connie M. Huddleston, Carol Aldridge, and Virginia Smith, Arcadia Publishing, 2005, {{ISBN|978-0-7385-4284-3}}. Retrieved January 20, 2010.</ref> The village thrived because besides the fertile bottomland, it afforded the combination of river access for transportation and fishing, and railroad transportation via the [[Illinois Central]] railroad.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/handbookkentuck00statgoog/page/n610 <!-- quote=\"Gilbertsville\" kentucky. -->]\"Handbook of Kentucky,\" by Hubert Vreeland, Commissioner of Agriculture. Louisville, Kentucky: The Globe Printing Co., 1908. Page 537. Retrieved January 20, 2010.</ref>\n\n===Modern Gilbertsville===\nThe construction of Kentucky Dam (1938\u20131944) meant the end for old Gilbertsville. The town was moved to its present site, initially called \"West Gilbertsville,\" with the geographic coordinates given above, by the time Kentucky Lake was impounded in the early 1940s.<ref name=Huddleston/> A notable event in the town's history was the dedication ceremony for Kentucky Dam on October 10, 1945, at which President [[Harry Truman]] gave the dedicatory speech.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=d0uu-j32elUC&pg=PA119&dq=%22Gilbertsville%22+kentucky&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&as_brr=3&cd=39#v=onepage&q=%22Gilbertsville%22%20kentucky&f=false] \"Conflict and crisis: the presidency of Harry S. Truman, 1945-1948.\" by Robert J. Donovan, University of Missouri Press, 1996. {{ISBN|978-0-8262-1066-1}}. Page 119. Retrieved January 20, 2010.</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FL4wAAAAIBAJ&sjid=pU4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=7038,3723457&dq=kentucky+gilbertsville&hl=en]\"Program for progress,\" St. Petersburg Times, October 11, 1945, page 4. Retrieved January 20, 2010</ref> Gilbertsville was a 6th class city from 1956 to 1976.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3Lac2FUSj_oC&pg=PA115&dq=%22Gilbertsville%22+kentucky&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&as_brr=3&cd=8#v=onepage&q=%22Gilbertsville%22%20kentucky&f=false] \"Kentucky Place Names,\" by Robert M. Rennick. The University Press of Kentucky, 1988, {{ISBN|978-0-8131-0179-8}}, Page 115. retrieved January 20, 2010.</ref> The town incorporated at its new site circa 1953. The town later abandoned its incorporated status in 1976 by a referendum. Before dissolving its charter, the town of 241 had a budget of $2,000 to $3,000 per year, which paid for a town marshal, street lights, and street repairs.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ByMqAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0UYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6662,25910&dq=kentucky+gilbertsville&hl=en]\"Gilbertsville concerned about 2 questions,\" by Bill Bergstrom, Associated Press. In the Daily News (Bowling Green, Kentucky), June 1, 1976.</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NrU0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=y2gFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1208,6357522&dq=kentucky+gilbertsville&hl=en]\"A still small voice.\" (Editorial). [[Kentucky New Era]] (Hopkinsville, Kentucky),May 28, 1976, page 21. Retrieved January 20, 2010.</ref>  It has been the site, for several decades, of the {{convert|25|acre|m2|adj=on}} Kentucky Sheriff's Boys and Girls Ranch, which has provided a free week-long summer camp for children ages 8\u201311, with total attendance of 30,000 through 2008.<ref>[http://www.timesleader.net/articles/stories/public/200806/04/4Okk_news.html]\"Sheriffs' Ranch open for summer session; boys, girls 8-11 invited to participate.\" The Times Leader (Princeton, Kentucky), June 4, 2008. Retrieved January 20, 2010</ref> Tourism related to the dams and lakes created nearby by [[Tennessee Valley Authority|TVA]] has driven the economy of the town since the 1940s. The town has an airport, an 18-hole golf course, a large marina, and has been the site of bass fishing tournaments<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/outdoors/tournaments/elite/news/story?id=3442226]\"On the ledge of success'\" by Lynn Burkhead, ESPNOutdoors.com August 13, 2008. Retrieved January 20, 2010</ref> and a car racing track.\n\n==Climate==\nThe climate in this area is characterized by hot, humid summers and generally mild to cool winters. According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, Gilbertsville has a [[humid subtropical climate]], abbreviated \"Cfa\" on climate maps.<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=322351&cityname=Gilbertsville%2C+Kentucky%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for Gilbertsville, Kentucky]</ref>\n\n==Annual events==\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://parks.ky.gov/calendar/default.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-05-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504133000/http://parks.ky.gov/calendar/default.aspx |archive-date=2014-05-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Arts and Crafts Festival\u2014Every Memorial Day Weekend the festival is located at the Old Beach Area and features handcrafted items by artists from Kentucky and neighboring states.\n* Earth Day Celebration\u2014Located at the Kentucky Dam Village Resort the festival features activities to celebrate Earth Day.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.uky.edu/KentuckyAtlas/ky-gilbertsville.html] Kentucky Atlas and Gazetteer, showing present location of Gilbertsville.\n\n{{Marshall County, Kentucky}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Marshall County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Populated places disestablished in 1976]]\n", "name_user": "An Errant Knight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Added link to Commons", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gilbertsville,_Kentucky"}
